text:
This headline... sigh. 

The FDA advisory panel has no power to authorize (or approve) vaccines. It makes recommendations to the FDA. The #Covid vax discussion today was about emergency use authorization, which is a lower bar than approval. https://t.co/EalDM86Oib

I hope parents know that the FDA advisory committee are really wrestling hard with the benefit/risk profile of the #COVID #vaccines for 5-11 yos, as can be seen in this thread. It's not a foregone conclusion going into this meeting. https://t.co/R4J3Z0uMYp
Highly recommend reading @matthewherper & @HelenBranswell 's live blog of the FDA advisory committee discussion on Covid vaccines for 5-11 yos. https://t.co/U2X0Z8oMwW

RT @SarahKarlin: Another day, another vaccine advisory committee for COVID-19.

With Halloween coming up, realizing is my first time living somewhere where kids will probably come trick or treating at my door. 
How do I go about this? How much candy do I get? Do I just leave a bowl outside (b/c Covid) or are kids super excited to ring doorbells so mask up?

"The virus, SARS-CoV-2, is what actually infects us, what actually transmits, what tests actually detect. Not COVID. (I am screaming into a void here...)" 

I'm screaming with you, @KatherineJWu. Don't get me started on authorized/approved.
